==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*airiz'', originally a comparitive form (= ‘earlier’).  Cognate with Old Frisian [[er|ēr]], Old Saxon [[er|ēr]] (Dutch [[eer]]), Old High German [[er|ēr]] (German [[eher]]), Gothic [[𐌰𐌹𐍂𐌹𐌶]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /æ:r/

====Adverb====
{{Unicode|'''ǣr'''}}
# [[soon]]
# [[earlier]], [[sooner]]
# [[previously]]
#:''manige halige lichaman ðe ær slepon aryson.'' Many saintly bodies that previously slept, arose. (''OE Gospels'')

====Preposition====
{{Unicode|'''ǣr'''}}
# [[before]] (in time)
#:''Ær his swylt-dæge.''  Before his death-day. (Cædmon’s ''Metrical Paraphrase'')

====Conjunction====
{{Unicode|'''ǣr'''}}
# [[before]] (in time)
#:''Ær heo wordum cwæþ...''  Before she said in words...  (Cædmon’s ''Metrical Paraphrase'')
# [[rather]] than, in preference to

